<chapter xml:id="normal-quotient-groups">
    <title>Normal and Quotient Groups</title>

    <section xml:id="sec-cosets">
      <title>Cosets and Equivalence Relations</title>

      <blockquote>
        <p>
          <q>Too much may be the equivalent of none at all.</q>
        </p>
        <attribution>Lee Loevinger</attribution>
      </blockquote>
      
      <definition xml:id="def-coset">
        <statement>
          <p>
            For any <m>N\leq G</m> and any <m>g\in G</m> let 
            <me>
              gN=\{gn|n\in N\}\;\text{and}\; Ng=\{ng|n\in N\}
            </me>
            be defined as a <em>left coset</em> and <em>right coset</em> of <m>N</m> in <m>G</m>, respectfully.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <remark>
        <p>
          Though mostly a matter of preference as aesthetics, we will focus primarily on left cosets.
        </p>
      </remark>

      <lemma xml:id="lem-cosetfacts">
        <title>Coset Equivalencies</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>H \leq G</m>. The following facts about left cosets are equivalent for <m>x,y \in G</m>:
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> belong to the same left coset of <m>H</m> in <m>G</m>,
                </p>
              </li>
    
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>x = yh</m> for some <m>h \in H</m>,
                </p>
              </li>
    
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>y = xh</m> for some <m>h \in H</m>,
                </p>
              </li>
    
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>y^{-1}x \in H</m>,
                </p>
              </li>
    
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>x^{-1}y \in H</m>,
                </p>
              </li>
    
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>xH = yH</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <proof>

          <p>
            <m>1. \Rightarrow 2.:</m> if <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> belong to the same left coset <m>gH</m> of <m>H</m> in <m>G</m> then <m>x=gh'</m> and <m>y=gh''</m> for some <m>h',h''\in H</m>, so <m>g=y(h'')^{-1}</m> and therefore <m>x=y(h'')^{-1}h'=yh</m> where <m>h=(h'')^{-1}h'\in H</m>.
          </p>
  
          <p>
            <m>2. \iff 3.:</m> <m>x=yh</m> for some <m>h \in H</m> <m>\iff</m> <m>y = xh^{-1}</m> and <m>h^{-1} \in H</m>.
          </p>
  
          <p>
            <m>2. \iff 4.:</m> <m>x=yh</m> for some <m>h \in H</m> <m>\iff</m> <m>y^{-1} x=h\in H</m>.
          </p>
  
          <p>
            <m>4. \iff 5.:</m> <m>y^{-1} x\in H \iff (y^{-1} x)^{-1}\in H \iff x^{-1}y\in H</m>.
          </p>
  
          <p>
            <m>2. \Rightarrow 6.:</m> Suppose <m>x = yh</m> for some <m>h \in H</m>, then by <m>2. \Rightarrow 3.</m> we also have <m>y = xh''</m> for some <m>h'' \in H</m>. Then we have <me>xH=\{xh'\mid h'\in H\}=\{yhh'\mid h'\in H\}\subset yH \text{ and}</me> <me>yH=\{yh'\mid h'\in H\}=\{xh''h'\mid h'\in H\}\subset xH,</me> thus <m>xH=yH</m>.
          </p>
  
          <p>
            <m>6. \Rightarrow 1.:</m> Since <m>e_G=e_H\in H</m>, we have <m>x=xe_G\in xH</m> and <m>y=ye_G\in yH</m>. If <m>xH=yH</m> then, <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> belong to the same left coset.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>

      <lemma xml:id="lem-cosetpartition">
        <statement>
          <p>
            For <m>H \leq G</m>, the collection of left cosets of <m>H</m> in <m>G</m> form a partition of <m>G</m>, and similarly for the collection of right cosets. That is,

            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  for all <m>x,y \in G</m>, either <m>xH = yH</m> or <m>xH \cap yH = \emptyset</m>
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\bigcup_{x\in G} xH=G</m>,                    
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\bigcup_{x\in G} xH=G</m>,                    
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
            and similarly for right cosets. Moreover all left and right cosets have the same cardinality: <m>|xH| = |Hx|=|H|</m> for any <m>x\in G</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>

        <proof>
          <p>
            Let me prove the assertions for right cosets. Clearly every element <m>g</m> of <m>G</m> belongs to at least one right coset, since <m>g \in Hg</m> (since <m>e \in H</m>). We need to show any two cosets are either identical or disjoint: if <m>Hx</m> and <m>Hy</m> share an element, then it follows from <m>1.\Rightarrow 6.</m> of Lemma <xref ref="lem-cosetfacts" /> that <m>Hx=Hy</m>. This proves that the right cosets partition <m>G</m>. To see that all right cosets have the same cardinality as <m>H</m>, define a function <me>\rho: H \to Hg</me> by <m>\rho(h) = hg</m>. Clearly <m>\rho</m> is onto and if <m>\rho(h) = \rho(h')</m> then <m>hg = h'g</m> and hence <m>h = h'</m>, so that <m>\rho</m> is also one-to-one.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>

      <corollary xml:id="cor-left-right-cosets">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>G</m> is a finite group and <m>H \leq G</m>, then 
            <me>
              \begin{aligned}
              |G| &amp; = |H| \cdot (\text{the number of left cosets of $H$ in $G$}) \\
              &amp; = |H| \cdot (\text{the number of right cosets of $H$ in $G$}). \\
              \end{aligned}
            </me> 
            In particular the number of left cosets of <m>H</m> in <m>G</m> is equal to the number of right cosets of <m>H</m> in <m>G</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Furthermore, even if <m>G</m> is not finite the number of left and right cosets of a subgroup <m>H\leq G</m> is still the same. <em>(Hint</em>: consider the map <m>gH\mapsto Hg^{-1}</m> and show it's a bijection. Why is the inverse needed?)

          </p>
        </statement>
      </corollary>

      <definition xml:id="def-index">
        <statement>
          <p>
            In finite groups, the common number of left or right cosets of a subgroup <m>H</m> in a group <m>G</m> is denoted as <m>[G:H]</m> and is called the <em>index</em> of <m>H</m> in <m>G</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <theorem xml:id="thm-lagrange">
        <title>Lagrange's Theorem</title>
        
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>H</m> is a subgroup of a finite group <m>G</m>, then <m>|H|</m> divides <m>|G|</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>

      <corollary xml:id="cor-lagrange">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>x\in G</m> and <m>G</m> is a finite group, then <m>|x|</m> divides <m>|G|</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </corollary>

      <corollary xml:id="cor-lagrange-index">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>G</m> is a finite group, then 
            <me>
              [G:H]=\frac{|G|}{|H|}
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </corollary>

      <theorem xml:id="thm-index-tower">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>G</m> be a group (possibly infinite) and <m>H \leq K</m> subgroups of <m>G</m>. Suppose <m>[G : H]</m> is finite. Prove that <m>[G : H] = [G : K][K : H].</m> (Hint: First prove this in the case <m>G</m> is a finite group. Then prove you can reduce to the finite case.)
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>

