    <section xml:id="sec-normal-subgroups">
      <title>Normal Subgroups</title>

      <blockquote>
        <p>
          <q>If you are always trying to be normal, you will never know how amazing you can be.</q>
        </p>
        <attribution>Maya Angelou</attribution>
      </blockquote>

      <definition xml:id="def-normal-subgroup">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A subgroup <m>N</m> of a group <m>G</m> is <em>normal</em> in <m>G</m>, written <m>N\nsg G</m>, if <m>gNg^{-1} = N</m> for all <m>g \in G</m>. 
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-equivdef-normal">
        <title>Equivalent Normal Definitions</title>
        
        
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>N</m> be a subgroup of a group <m>G</m>. The following are equivalent: 
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>N \nsg G</m>
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>gNg^{-1}\subseteq N</m> for all <m>g \in G</m>. 
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>gN = Ng</m> for all <m>g \in G</m>. 
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>

      <example>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                The trivial subgroups <m>\{e\}</m>, <m>G</m> of a group <m>G</m> are normal. 
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Any subgroup of an abelian group is normal. 
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                For any group <m>G</m>, <m>Z(G)\nsg G</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </example>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Show that being a normal subgroup is not a transitive relation.
        </p>

        <proof>
          <p>
            Consider <me>V=\{e, (1 2)(3 4), (1 3)(2 4), (1 4)(2 3)\}</me> one can show that <m>V \nsg S_4</m> and, since <m>V</m> is abelian (<xref ref="order-4-abelian"/>), the subgroup <m>H = \{e,(12)(34)\}</m> is normal in <m>V</m>. But <m>H</m> is not normal in <m>S_4</m>, since for example
            <me>
              (1 3) [(1 2)(3 4)] (1 3)^{-1} = (3 2)(1 4) \notin H.
            </me> 
          </p>
        </proof>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove that if <m>f:G\to H</m> is a group homomorphism and <m>K\nsg H</m> then the preimage of <m>K</m>, <m>f^{-1}(K)=\{g\in G | f(g)\in K\}</m>, is a normal subgroup of <m>G</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
            
            <li>
              <p>
                Show that if <m>f:G\to H</m> is a group homomorphism and <m>L \nsg G</m> then <m>f(L)</m> need not be a normal subgroup of <m>H</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Show that any subgroup of index two is normal. This means: show that if <m>G</m> is a group, <m>H</m> is a subgroup and <m>[G:H]=2</m>, i.e the number of left (or right) cosets of <m>H</m> in <m>G</m> is two, then <m>H</m> is normal. 
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Let <m>H</m> be a subgroup and <m>x\in G</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>xHx^{-1}</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>H\cong xHx^{-1}</m> 
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Suppose <m>|H|=n</m> and <m>H</m> is the only subgroup of <m>G</m> of order <m>n</m>. Prove that <m>H</m> is normal.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Let <m>H</m> and <m>K</m> be normal subgroups of a group <m>G</m> such that <m>H\cap K=\{1\}</m>. Prove that <m>xy=yx</m> for all <m>x\in H, y\in K</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Let <m>G</m> be a group and <m>S</m> a subset of <m>G</m>. Let <m>H=\langle S \rangle</m>. Prove that <m>H\nsg G</m> if and only if <m>gsg^{-1}\in H</m> for every <m>s\in S</m> and <m>g\in G</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Let <m>G</m> be a group and let <m>A \subseteq G</m> be a set. The <em>normal subgroup generated by <m>A</m></em>, denoted <m>\langle A \rangle ^N</m>, is the intersection of all the normal subgroups of <m>G</m> that contain <m>A</m>. 
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Show that <m>\langle A \rangle ^N</m> is a normal subgroup of <m>G</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Show that the elements of <m>\langle A \rangle ^N</m> can be described as 
                <me>
                  \langle A \rangle ^N= \{ g_1a_1^{i_1}g_1^{-1} \dots g_ma_m^{i_m}g_m^{-1} \mid m \geq 0, a_j \in A, g_j \in G, i_j \in \{1,-1\}, \forall 1\leq j\leq m\}.
                </me> 
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </problem>
      
      <problem>
        <p>
          Let <m>G</m> be a group, <m>S=\{aba^{-1}b^{-1}\mid a,b\in G\}</m>, and <m>H=\langle S \rangle</m>. Prove that <m>H\nsg G</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Let <m>G</m> be a group with subgroups <m>H, K</m>. Recall the notation <me>HK=\{hk \mid h\in H, k\in K\}.</me> 
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>HK\leq G</m> if and only if <m>HK=KH</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Prove that if either one of <m>H</m> or <m>K</m> is a normal subgroup of <m>G</m>, then <m>HK\leq G</m> and <m>HK=KH=\langle H\cup K\rangle</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          In <m>D_{2n}</m>, let <m>H=\langle s\rangle</m> and <m>K=\langle r\rangle</m>. Then <m>HK=KH=D_{2n}</m> but of course <m>r</m> and <m>s</m> do not commute. The fact that <m>HK=KH</m> can also be justified by observing that <m>K\nsg D_{2n}</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Let <m>G</m> be a group and <m>\operatorname{Aut}(G)</m> be its automorphism group. In Problem 7 on HW # 2, you proved that for each <m>g\in G</m>, the function <m>\psi_g:G\to G</m> defined by <m>\psi_g(x)=gxg^{-1}</m> for all <m>x\in G</m> is an automorphism of <m>G</m>. Further, you proved the set <m>\operatorname{Inn}(G):=\{\psi_g \mid g\in G\}</m>, called the set of <em>inner automorphisms</em> of <m>G</m>, is a subgroup of <m>\operatorname{Aut}(G)</m>. Prove that <m>\operatorname{Inn}(G)\triangleleft \operatorname{Aut}(G)</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Let <m>G</m> be a finite group. Prove that the number of elements in the set <m>S=\{g\in G\mid g\neq g^{-1}\}</m> is even. Conclude that a group of even order must have an element of order <m>2</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Let <m>G</m> be a finite group, <m>H</m> and <m>N</m> subgroups such that <m>|H|</m> and <m>[G : N]</m> = are relatively prime and <m>N\nsg G</m> . Prove that <m>H \subseteq N</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
          <p>
            Let <m>G</m> be a group. A subgroup <m>H</m> of <m>G</m> is called a <em>characteristic subgroup</em> of <m>G</m> if <m>\a(H)=H</m> for every automorphism <m>\a</m> of <m>G</m>. Show that if <m>H</m> is a characteristic subgroup of <m>N</m> and <m>N</m> is a normal subgroup of <m>G</m>, then <m>H</m> is a normal subgroup of <m>G</m>.
          </p>

          <solution>
            <p>
              Let <m>G</m> be a group, <m>N</m> is a normal subgroup of <m>G</m>, and <m>H</m> a characteristic subgroup of <m>N</m>. Let <m>g\in G</m> and consider the automorphism <m>a_g:G\to G</m> given by <m>a_g(g')=gg'g^{-1}</m>.
            </p>
  
            <p>
              Let <m>n\in N</m> and notice <m>a_g(n)=gng\inv\in N</m>, as <m>N\nsg G</m>. Thus <m>a_g:N\to N</m> is well defined. Let <m>n\in N</m>. As <m>gNg\inv=N</m>, we can write <m>n=gn'g\inv</m> for some <m>n'\in N</m>. Then <m>a_g(n')=gn'g\inv=n</m>, making <m>a_g</m> surjective. As <m>|N|=|N|</m> we see that <m>a_g</m> is a bijection. The homomorphism piece we get for free from <m>G</m>, making <m>a_g\in\Aut(N)</m>.
            </p>
  
            <p>
              Let <m>h\in H</m>. As <m>H</m> is a characteristic subgroup of <m>N</m>, we see that <m>a_g(h)=ghg\inv=h</m> for all <m>h\in H</m> and for all <m>g\in G</m>. Thus <m>H</m> is normal in <m>G</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Let <m>G</m> be a group with a subgroup <m>H</m> so that <m>[G : H] = n &lt; \infty</m>. (a) Prove that there is a normal subgroup of <m>G, N</m> , so that <m>N\subseteq H</m> and <m>[G : N ] \leq n!.</m> (b) Prove that if <m>G</m> is finitely generated, there are most finitely many subgroups with index <m>n</m>.(Hint: you might want to consider maps <m>G\to S_n</m>.)
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
					Let <m>G</m> be a group, and <m>H, K \leq G</m> be subgroups of <m>G</m>. 
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Give an example of <m>G, H,</m> and <m>K</m> such that <m>HK</m> is not a subgroup of <m>G</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Suppose now that <m>H\nsg G</m> and <m>[G : H] = p</m>, where <m>p</m> is prime. Prove that either <m>K \leq H</m> or <m>G = KH</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
				</p>

        <proof>

          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>G=S_3</m>, <m>H=\langle(12)\rangle</m>, and <m>K=\langle(13)\rangle</m>. Notice that <m>H\cap K=\{e\}</m>, and thus <m>|HK|=4</m>, (<xref provisional="empty"/>) which does not divide <m>6</m>. Thus <m>HK</m> is not a subgroup of <m>G</m>, as this would contradict <xref text="title" ref="thm-lagrange" />.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Suppose there exists some <m>k\in K</m> such that <m>k\not\in H</m>. We examine <m>kH\in G/H</m>. Notice that since <m>G/H</m> has prime order it is cyclic, and thus generated by any non-identity element, such as <m>kH</m>. Thus any element in <m>G/H</m> can be written in the form <m>k^iH</m>, and any element in <m>G</m> can subsequently be written as <m>k^ih</m> for some <m>h\in H</m>. Thus <m>G=KH</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </proof>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Let <m>G</m> be a finite group and <m>K</m> a subgroup of <m>G</m> such that: <m>[G : K] = 2</m>, <m>K</m> is simple, and <m>Z(G) = \{e\}</m>. Prove that the only normal subgroups of <m>G</m> are <m>\{e\}, K</m>, and <m>G</m>. (Hint: Let H be a normal subgroup of G. Then H ∩K is a normal subgroup of K.)
        </p>
      </problem>

      <exercises>

        <exercisegroup>
          <title>Computations and Examples</title>
          <introduction>
            <p>
            </p>
          </introduction>
      
