    <section xml:id="sec-quotient-groups">
      <title>Quotient Groups</title>

      <lemma xml:id="lem-quotient-surj-hom">
        <statement>
          <p>
            For any group <m>G</m> and normal subgroup <m>N</m> of <m>G</m>, the map <m>\pi:G \to G/N</m> defined by <m>\pi(g)=gN</m> is a surjective group homomorphism with kernel <m>\operatorname{Ker}(\pi)=N</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>

        <proof>
          <p>
            Surjectivity is immediate from the definition. The group homomorphism property follows from the computation below which uses the definition of <m>\pi</m> and the rule for multiplying cosets in <m>G/N</m>: <me>\pi(gg')=(gg')N=gN\cdot g'N=\pi(g)\pi(g').</me> Finally, using Lemma <xref ref="lem:cosets" />, we have <m>\operatorname{Ker}(\pi)=\{g\in G\mid gN=e_GN\}=N</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>

      <corollary xml:id="cor-norm-iff-ker">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A subgroup <m>N</m> of a group <m>G</m> is normal in <m>G</m> if and only if <m>N</m> is the kernel of a homomorphism with domain <m>G</m>
          </p>
        </statement>

